Spring Boot:
    Spring Boot is an open-source Java framework built on top of the Spring Framework that simplifies the development of production-ready applications.
    It eliminates much of the boilerplate configuration traditionally required in Spring applications.

Core Philosophy:
Spring Boot follows three key principles:
  Convention over Configuration — sensible defaults are provided out of the box, so you only configure what you need to change.
  Opinionated Defaults — it makes decisions for you (e.g., which libraries to use), so you can focus on business logic.
  Standalone Applications — apps run independently without needing an external server like Tomcat or JBoss.

Key Features:
1. Auto-Configuration:
    Spring Boot automatically configures your application based on the dependencies present on the classpath.
    For example, if spring-boot-starter-web is included, it auto-configures an embedded Tomcat server, Spring MVC, Jackson for JSON, etc.
2. Spring Boot Starters
    Starters are pre-packaged dependency descriptors that bundle related libraries together:
    Starter                       Purposes
    pring-boot-starter-web        REST APIs & MVC
    spring-boot-starter-data-jpa  Database with JPA/Hibernate
    spring-boot-starter-security  Authentication & Authorization
    spring-boot-starter-test      Testing (JUnit, Mockito)
    spring-boot-starter-actuator  Monitoring & Metrics
3. Embedded Server
    No need to deploy a WAR file to an external server. 
    Spring Boot embeds Tomcat, Jetty, or Undertow directly into your JAR — just run java -jar app.jar.
4. Spring Boot Actuator
    Provides production-ready endpoints for monitoring:
      /actuator/health — app health status
      /actuator/metrics — performance metrics
      /actuator/env — environment properties
      /actuator/info — custom app info
5. Spring Boot DevTools
    Enables hot reloading during development — changes reflect without restarting the server.

The Architecture & Flow:
The lifecycle of a Spring Boot application generally follows this path:
    Deployment: The user triggers the main method in a class annotated with @SpringBootApplication.
    Bootstrap: The SpringApplication.run() method starts the context.
    Component Scanning: Spring looks for classes annotated with @Component, @Service, @Repository, or @Controller.
    Auto-Configuration: Based on the libraries found in the pom.xml or build.gradle, Spring Boot applies the necessary configurations.
    Execution: The embedded server starts, and the application becomes ready to handle requests.

Core Annotations:
Annotation                  Purpose
@SpringBootApplication      Entry point — combines @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration, @ComponentScan
@RestController             Marks a class as a REST API controller
@RequestMapping             Maps HTTP routes to methods
@Service                    Marks a service class
@Repository                 Marks a data access class
@Autowired                  Dependency injection
@Entity                     Maps a class to a database table
@Value                      Injects values from application.properties

Why Use Spring Boot?
Speed: Go from an empty folder to a running "Hello World" REST API in minutes.
Microservices Ready: Its lightweight nature and ease of deployment make it the industry standard for microservice architectures.
Large Community: Excellent documentation and massive community support for troubleshooting.
Externalized Configuration: Easily manage different environments (Dev, Test, Prod) using application.
                            properties or application.yml files.

Spring Boot Ecosystem:
Spring Boot integrates seamlessly with:
      Spring Security — JWT, OAuth2, role-based access
      Spring Cloud — microservices, service discovery (Eureka), API Gateway
      Spring Data — JPA, MongoDB, Redis, Elasticsearch
      Spring Batch — batch processing
      Spring Kafka / RabbitMQ — message queues

