Exception Handling in Spring Boot:
Why Exception Handling Matters
    Without proper handling:          With proper handling:
    ─────────────────────             ─────────────────────
    500 Internal Server Error         { 
    java.lang.NullPointerException      "status": 404,
       at com.app.Service.java:45        "error": "User Not Found",
       at com.app.Controller.java:12     "message": "No user with id 99",
       ...stack trace exposed 😱         "timestamp": "2026-04-01T10:00:00"
                                       }  ✅ Clean & safe
@ExceptionHandler- Handles exceptions within a single controller:
@RestController
public class UserController {
    @GetMapping("/users/{id}")
    public User getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return userService.findById(id); // may throw UserNotFoundException
    }
    // Handles ONLY within this controller
    @ExceptionHandler(UserNotFoundException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleNotFound(UserNotFoundException ex) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(404).body(ex.getMessage());
    }
}
Limitation — only works in the controller it's defined in. Not reusable.

@ControllerAdvice / @RestControllerAdvice -Handles exceptions globally across ALL controllers:

@ControllerAdvice       = @Component + global exception handling (returns View)
@RestControllerAdvice   = @ControllerAdvice + @ResponseBody (returns JSON)

@ResponseStatus
Directly maps an exception class to an HTTP status code:
@ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND)           // ← auto returns 404
public class UserNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
    public UserNotFoundException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}
